3
00:00:22,301 --> 00:00:25,937
Screaming like a little girl
won't help me fly this baby!

4
00:00:28,574 --> 00:00:30,508
Uh...

5
00:00:30,509 --> 00:00:31,742
Captain to co-captain...

6
00:00:31,743 --> 00:00:33,778
"Captain" implies
that you actually know

7
00:00:33,779 --> 00:00:35,179
how to fly this thing.

8
00:00:35,180 --> 00:00:36,681
Chill! It's just
like <i>Nitromaniacs.</i>

9
00:00:36,682 --> 00:00:38,850
That's a video game!
This is an airplane!

10
00:00:38,851 --> 00:00:41,152
And when my mom
finds out we stole it...

11
00:00:41,153 --> 00:00:43,754
We didn't steal it.
It's Jensen property.

12
00:00:43,755 --> 00:00:46,824
I'm a Jensen employee,
and we're on a Jensen mission.

13
00:00:46,825 --> 00:00:48,860
She'll buy that!
Oh, I'm so dead!

14
00:00:48,861 --> 00:00:51,095
Not if we get back
the molecular assembler

15
00:00:51,096 --> 00:00:52,797
and save the world!

16
00:00:52,798 --> 00:00:54,999
Trust me, you'll go from
juvie to hero in one night.

17
00:00:55,000 --> 00:00:56,434
Assuming I survive this--

18
00:00:56,435 --> 00:00:57,735
- Hang on!
- Ahh!

19
00:01:23,262 --> 00:01:25,730
Brody, how many times
do I have to tell you

20
00:01:25,731 --> 00:01:26,731
to use a glass?

21
00:01:28,433 --> 00:01:30,468
Brody!

22
00:01:33,906 --> 00:01:35,172
Ah! Oh!

23
00:01:35,173 --> 00:01:36,507
Ah...

24
00:01:42,548 --> 00:01:44,015
Thanks!

25
00:01:44,016 --> 00:01:45,716
Keys! Keys!
Has anybody seen my keys?

26
00:01:45,717 --> 00:01:46,784
Entryway table.

27
00:01:46,785 --> 00:01:48,252
Not there.

28
00:01:48,253 --> 00:01:50,254
The pants you were
wearing last night.

29
00:01:50,255 --> 00:01:51,255
Here.

30
00:01:51,256 --> 00:01:52,757
You're a genius!
Ow! Ow!

31
00:01:52,758 --> 00:01:54,158
So I've been told.

32
00:01:55,160 --> 00:01:58,029
Hey, Mom, I don't
feel that great.

33
00:01:58,030 --> 00:01:59,297
Can I stay home?

34
00:01:59,298 --> 00:02:01,432
You don't seem feverish.

35
00:02:01,433 --> 00:02:02,466
Well...

36
00:02:03,468 --> 00:02:05,536
It--it's more in my chest.

37
00:02:05,537 --> 00:02:06,871
You stay up
late texting,

38
00:02:06,872 --> 00:02:09,173
leave your homework
to the last second,

39
00:02:09,174 --> 00:02:10,841
and now all of a sudden
you're sick?

40
00:02:10,842 --> 00:02:12,376
I don't think so!

41
00:02:12,377 --> 00:02:14,111
But what if I infect
the whole school?

42
00:02:14,112 --> 00:02:17,214
Luckily, your father's
specialty is immunology!

43
00:02:22,888 --> 00:02:24,255
Brody...

44
00:02:27,025 --> 00:02:29,594
Listen, I know you
find school boring.

45
00:02:29,595 --> 00:02:31,195
Just try to make
the most of it.

46
00:02:32,631 --> 00:02:34,031
Whatever.

47
00:02:50,382 --> 00:02:52,583
-  everything OK?
- Fine.

48
00:02:52,584 --> 00:02:53,951
Are you sure?

49
00:02:53,952 --> 00:02:56,988
We'll talk about it
another time.

50
00:02:56,989 --> 00:02:58,856
Suit yourself.

51
00:02:58,857 --> 00:03:02,059
Oh, I gotta go. I booked
satellite time for my students.

52
00:03:02,060 --> 00:03:03,094
I can't be late.

53
00:03:03,095 --> 00:03:04,462
Whoa! I already am late!

54
00:03:30,422 --> 00:03:32,456
<i>This is Claire Thompson.</i>
<i>We're not home.</i>

55
00:03:32,457 --> 00:03:34,592
But you can leave a message
<i>after the beep.</i>

56
00:03:50,208 --> 00:03:52,009
<i>You stay up late...</i>

57
00:03:52,010 --> 00:03:53,778
...last possible second.

58
00:03:53,779 --> 00:03:55,513
You don't seem feverish.

59
00:03:56,515 --> 00:03:57,815
Infect the whole school...

60
00:04:03,889 --> 00:04:06,791
<i>Marshall Heights High School.</i>
<i>This is Mrs. Johnson.</i>

61
00:04:06,792 --> 00:04:08,359
<i>How may I help you?</i>

62
00:04:08,360 --> 00:04:10,494
<i>This is Claire Thompson.</i>
<i>Brody stayed up late.</i>

63
00:04:10,495 --> 00:04:11,996
<i>He seems feverish.</i>

64
00:04:11,997 --> 00:04:13,998
<i>We don't want him to</i>
<i>infect the whole school.</i>

65
00:04:13,999 --> 00:04:15,366
We're gonna keep him home.

66
00:04:15,367 --> 00:04:16,834
<i>Thanks for calling.</i>

67
00:04:23,608 --> 00:04:26,010
If the com sat is
at current position,

68
00:04:26,011 --> 00:04:27,812
200 miles above the surface,

69
00:04:27,813 --> 00:04:30,014
and travelling
at a constant speed,

70
00:04:30,015 --> 00:04:32,917
who can tell me how long
we'll maintain contact

71
00:04:32,918 --> 00:04:34,819
at maximum-signal performance?

72
00:04:35,887 --> 00:04:37,054
Anyone?

73
00:04:40,025 --> 00:04:42,059
7.025 minutes.

74
00:04:43,795 --> 00:04:46,997
Quiz on chapters
10 through 14, guys, Monday!

75
00:04:46,998 --> 00:04:48,432
Please be prepared!

76
00:04:50,202 --> 00:04:51,702
Nice work, Josh.

77
00:04:51,703 --> 00:04:53,504
Can't believe
we got satellite time!

78
00:04:53,505 --> 00:04:55,473
I called in a favor.

79
00:04:55,474 --> 00:04:58,542
I just thought the class
would be more into it, though.

80
00:04:58,543 --> 00:05:00,511
Can I ask you
a question?

81
00:05:00,512 --> 00:05:02,079
- Sure.
- You went to MIT.

82
00:05:02,080 --> 00:05:03,714
Graduated with
2 advanced degrees.

83
00:05:03,715 --> 00:05:06,217
Instead of telling us
about the latest tech,

84
00:05:06,218 --> 00:05:08,419
why aren't you
designing it?

85
00:05:11,389 --> 00:05:14,091
I have to take this.
I'll see you Monday.

86
00:05:15,160 --> 00:05:16,427
Claire Thompson.

87
00:05:16,428 --> 00:05:18,562
<i>Hi, Mrs. Thompson!</i>
<i>It's Mrs. Banks</i>

88
00:05:18,563 --> 00:05:21,031
I emailed Brody
his homework assignment.

89
00:05:21,032 --> 00:05:22,199
Why?

90
00:05:22,200 --> 00:05:24,235
The office said you called.

91
00:05:24,236 --> 00:05:25,236
I called?

92
00:05:25,237 --> 00:05:27,271
<i>About his being sick today.</i>

93
00:05:28,874 --> 00:05:29,907
Right.

94
00:05:29,908 --> 00:05:31,876
I hope he feels better.

95
00:05:33,578 --> 00:05:35,112
Not likely!

96
00:05:35,113 --> 00:05:37,248
Not after
I get done with him.

97
00:05:41,553 --> 00:05:43,320
E...

98
00:05:45,791 --> 00:05:48,626
I...

99
00:05:48,627 --> 00:05:51,128
O...

100
00:05:51,129 --> 00:05:52,797
U...

101
00:05:54,032 --> 00:05:55,432
Whoo!

102
00:05:56,568 --> 00:05:59,036
It's like he can't
get a full breath.

103
00:05:59,037 --> 00:06:01,205
Does he have
a history of asthma?

104
00:06:01,206 --> 00:06:02,640
- No.
- Huh. Bronchitis?

105
00:06:02,641 --> 00:06:03,674
No.

106
00:06:03,675 --> 00:06:05,309
- Laryngitis?
- No.

107
00:06:05,310 --> 00:06:06,410
Sinusitis?

108
00:06:06,411 --> 00:06:07,978
- No.
- Rhinitis?

109
00:06:07,979 --> 00:06:09,013
No.

110
00:06:09,014 --> 00:06:10,681
- Pneumothoraxis?
- No.

111
00:06:10,682 --> 00:06:12,416
- Aspergillosis?
- Mm-mmm.

112
00:06:12,417 --> 00:06:13,851
Hmm...

113
00:06:15,854 --> 00:06:17,221
You a smoker?

114
00:06:17,222 --> 00:06:18,222
No, sir.

115
00:06:18,223 --> 00:06:20,491
That's good.
Keep it up.

116
00:06:21,626 --> 00:06:23,160
OK...

117
00:06:23,161 --> 00:06:24,562
Open wide.

118
00:06:26,865 --> 00:06:28,766
Ahh...

119
00:06:30,068 --> 00:06:31,936
OK, I found
the problem, I think.

120
00:06:31,937 --> 00:06:33,737
Your son...

121
00:06:35,307 --> 00:06:39,176
has a very bad case
of rhinosis...

122
00:06:39,177 --> 00:06:41,178
gummerius...

123
00:06:41,179 --> 00:06:42,813
Is that serious?

124
00:06:42,814 --> 00:06:44,815
Not very...

125
00:06:44,816 --> 00:06:46,317
Quint!

126
00:06:48,420 --> 00:06:51,889
I am so sorry to have
wasted your time, Doctor!

127
00:06:51,890 --> 00:06:53,891
It could have been worse.

128
00:06:55,193 --> 00:06:57,194
It could have been
a real worm.

129
00:07:02,601 --> 00:07:03,868
Rough day?

130
00:07:06,037 --> 00:07:08,105
Nothing worth
talking about.

131
00:07:09,474 --> 00:07:11,175
What are you doing here?

132
00:07:11,176 --> 00:07:12,610
- It's Brody.
- What now?

133
00:07:12,611 --> 00:07:15,346
- He cut school, again!
- What do you mean, again?

134
00:07:15,347 --> 00:07:17,748
The school said that
he used your letterhead

135
00:07:17,749 --> 00:07:19,984
to write notes 3 times
in the last 2 months

136
00:07:19,985 --> 00:07:23,187
and that the next absence would
require a call from one of us.

137
00:07:23,188 --> 00:07:24,421
So he faked my voice.

138
00:07:24,422 --> 00:07:25,890
OK, how did he do that?

139
00:07:25,891 --> 00:07:27,291
I have no idea,

140
00:07:27,292 --> 00:07:29,860
but he was convincing enough
to fool his teachers.

141
00:07:29,861 --> 00:07:31,028
Ha-ha! Clever kid!

142
00:07:31,029 --> 00:07:32,663
Too clever for
his own good!

143
00:07:32,664 --> 00:07:34,198
Maybe that's the problem!

144
00:07:34,199 --> 00:07:36,166
Maybe he's in
the wrong environment--

145
00:07:36,167 --> 00:07:37,501
Matt, don't start.

146
00:07:37,502 --> 00:07:40,571
Not talking about it
won't solve the problem, Claire.

147
00:07:40,572 --> 00:07:42,273
What is it?

148
00:07:48,246 --> 00:07:49,513
Ingrid?

149
00:07:55,487 --> 00:07:58,122
Claire, what a surprise
to see you here.

150
00:07:58,123 --> 00:07:59,423
Uh...

151
00:07:59,424 --> 00:08:00,524
ditto.

152
00:08:01,893 --> 00:08:03,594
So, uh...

153
00:08:03,595 --> 00:08:06,463
to what do we owe the honor
after all these years?

154
00:08:06,464 --> 00:08:09,433
The Jensen Project
is in trouble.

155
00:08:09,434 --> 00:08:12,369
I came to ask Claire
to help us.

156
00:08:12,370 --> 00:08:13,370
Me?

157
00:08:13,371 --> 00:08:15,706
You want me to help you?

158
00:08:17,575 --> 00:08:21,745
OK, why don't we all sit down
and we'll talk about this--

159
00:08:21,746 --> 00:08:25,082
You two can talk all you want.
I'm out of here!

160
00:08:25,083 --> 00:08:26,383
Claire...

161
00:08:27,385 --> 00:08:29,119
Honey, wait.

162
00:08:30,322 --> 00:08:31,622
Claire... Claire!

163
00:08:31,623 --> 00:08:33,257
- No! No! No!
- Hey!

164
00:08:33,258 --> 00:08:35,459
When I needed her,
she was not there for me!

165
00:08:35,460 --> 00:08:37,428
There is no way
I'm gonna...

166
00:08:42,434 --> 00:08:43,968
Let's...

167
00:08:52,477 --> 00:08:54,778
When Edwin humiliated you...

168
00:08:54,779 --> 00:08:56,747
Today...

169
00:08:56,748 --> 00:09:00,084
we've just witnessed
utter failure.

170
00:09:01,586 --> 00:09:03,854
You were understandably
hurt by what he said.

171
00:09:03,855 --> 00:09:05,222
Hurt?

172
00:09:05,223 --> 00:09:06,390
As her mentor,

173
00:09:06,391 --> 00:09:09,126
I should have recognized
the limitations

174
00:09:09,127 --> 00:09:11,095
of her talent
and intellect.

175
00:09:11,096 --> 00:09:12,930
- I was devastated.
- I know.

176
00:09:12,931 --> 00:09:14,331
What he said was cruel.

177
00:09:14,332 --> 00:09:15,833
Your work...

178
00:09:15,834 --> 00:09:17,901
isn't good enough.

179
00:09:18,970 --> 00:09:21,572
You... aren't good enough.

180
00:09:23,274 --> 00:09:26,677
<i>I admired Edwin more than</i>
<i>you could possibly imagine.</i>

181
00:09:28,046 --> 00:09:29,947
I think what hurt
more than his words

182
00:09:29,948 --> 00:09:32,116
was knowing how badly
I disappointed him.

183
00:09:32,117 --> 00:09:35,352
Nobody understands better
than me how it's haunted you.

184
00:09:35,353 --> 00:09:37,221
And I know you don't
wanna hear this,

185
00:09:37,222 --> 00:09:39,523
but I still think
we should talk to Ingrid.

186
00:09:39,524 --> 00:09:40,591
Why?

187
00:09:40,592 --> 00:09:42,960
Because maybe it's
an opportunity!

188
00:09:42,961 --> 00:09:45,529
What are you talking about?
An opportunity for what?

189
00:09:45,530 --> 00:09:46,563
I don't know!

190
00:09:46,564 --> 00:09:48,632
I don't know.
To revisit the past!

191
00:09:48,633 --> 00:09:51,635
To somehow repair the damage
that was done to you.

192
00:09:51,636 --> 00:09:53,170
I have no idea.
But it...

193
00:09:53,171 --> 00:09:56,774
It can't hurt to hear
what Ingrid has to say!

194
00:09:58,009 --> 00:09:59,410
Please, Claire.

195
00:10:00,412 --> 00:10:01,779
Do this for me.

196
00:10:03,481 --> 00:10:05,049
Edwin left
the Jensen Project.

197
00:10:05,050 --> 00:10:07,384
Took his whole team...

198
00:10:07,385 --> 00:10:09,753
and several
experimental projects,

199
00:10:09,754 --> 00:10:10,854
including yours.

200
00:10:10,855 --> 00:10:12,423
So? It didn't work. Remember?

201
00:10:12,424 --> 00:10:14,024
It works now.

202
00:10:15,226 --> 00:10:16,693
After you left,

203
00:10:16,694 --> 00:10:20,364
Edwin continued your research
on electro nanobots.

204
00:10:20,365 --> 00:10:21,365
He what?

205
00:10:21,366 --> 00:10:22,699
And over the years,

206
00:10:22,700 --> 00:10:24,835
he perfected the work
that you created.

207
00:10:24,836 --> 00:10:26,904
This technology can save
millions of lives.

208
00:10:26,905 --> 00:10:29,540
It can just as easily
destroy millions.

209
00:10:29,541 --> 00:10:31,375
I don't follow you. What--

210
00:10:31,376 --> 00:10:34,478
Nanobots are computers
the size of molecules.

211
00:10:34,479 --> 00:10:36,647
They can be implanted
in human tissue.

212
00:10:36,648 --> 00:10:38,015
In a battle,
for example,

213
00:10:38,016 --> 00:10:39,316
a soldier is wounded.

214
00:10:39,317 --> 00:10:41,318
If he's implanted
with a nanobot,

215
00:10:41,319 --> 00:10:43,954
it could tell the medics
his exact location.

216
00:10:43,955 --> 00:10:46,690
It could even stabilize
his bodily functions.

217
00:10:46,691 --> 00:10:47,724
That's good, no?

218
00:10:47,725 --> 00:10:49,159
Unless the enemy
gets control

219
00:10:49,160 --> 00:10:51,028
of the computer that
manages the bots.

220
00:10:51,029 --> 00:10:53,263
They could wipe out
an entire army

221
00:10:53,264 --> 00:10:56,967
by giving every soldier
in the field a massive coronary.

222
00:10:56,968 --> 00:10:59,103
By simply
pressing a button.

223
00:11:00,772 --> 00:11:02,806
This technology
could be a blessing,

224
00:11:02,807 --> 00:11:04,208
or it could be
a nightmare,

225
00:11:04,209 --> 00:11:06,110
depending on
who's controlling it.

226
00:11:06,111 --> 00:11:08,145
And right now
that's Edwin?

227
00:11:08,146 --> 00:11:09,913
That's why
I've come to you.

228
00:11:09,914 --> 00:11:12,783
When Edwin left,
he wiped the drives clean.

229
00:11:12,784 --> 00:11:14,985
I have no idea how he got
from my model to--

230
00:11:14,986 --> 00:11:17,087
You have more of an idea
than anyone else!

231
00:11:17,088 --> 00:11:19,156
Certainly anyone else
in the Jensen family!

232
00:11:19,157 --> 00:11:21,458
I haven't been in the family
in a long time.

233
00:11:21,459 --> 00:11:23,260
Why not go to
the authorities?

234
00:11:23,261 --> 00:11:26,463
The negative media spin could
destroy the Jensen Project

235
00:11:26,464 --> 00:11:28,832
and all of the good
work we've done!

236
00:11:28,833 --> 00:11:30,234
We need you!

237
00:11:30,235 --> 00:11:33,303
We need both of you,
and we need you now.

238
00:11:40,578 --> 00:11:42,379
Whoo!

239
00:11:45,216 --> 00:11:48,652
Hey, Jimmy, I thought
$20 bought me another...

240
00:11:50,488 --> 00:11:51,722
What were you thinking?

241
00:11:51,723 --> 00:11:53,190
That you'd never find out.

242
00:11:53,191 --> 00:11:54,825
How'd you know
where I was, anyway?

243
00:11:54,826 --> 00:11:57,494
Your mom used a satellite
to track your cell phone.

244
00:11:57,495 --> 00:11:58,729
What?

245
00:11:58,730 --> 00:11:59,696
You pretended
to be me

246
00:11:59,697 --> 00:12:00,931
so you could
skip school.

247
00:12:00,932 --> 00:12:03,333
Not cool. Oh, and you
are totally grounded.

248
00:12:03,334 --> 00:12:04,468
Look, I can explain.

249
00:12:04,469 --> 00:12:06,370
I was testing rates
of noise reduction

250
00:12:06,371 --> 00:12:07,704
in isolated
audio signals.

251
00:12:07,705 --> 00:12:08,906
I wrote an app
that can--

252
00:12:08,907 --> 00:12:10,040
It doesn't matter.

253
00:12:10,041 --> 00:12:11,475
You lied to the school

254
00:12:11,476 --> 00:12:12,776
and you lied to us.

255
00:12:12,777 --> 00:12:15,345
OK, I'm sorry.
Where are we going?

256
00:12:15,346 --> 00:12:18,148
We're sending you
to military school.

257
00:12:19,617 --> 00:12:21,018
What?

258
00:12:21,019 --> 00:12:24,288
Look, Mom, I'll change!
Can't we talk about this?

259
00:12:24,289 --> 00:12:26,590
You're not going
to military school!

260
00:12:26,591 --> 00:12:28,125
Then where are we going?

261
00:12:28,126 --> 00:12:30,093
- We're going back.
- Back where?

262
00:12:30,094 --> 00:12:31,628
To save the day, I hope!

263
00:12:31,629 --> 00:12:35,365
And while we're at it,
maybe the world!

264
00:12:46,930 --> 00:12:49,364
Why did Edwin choose now
to leave the Project?

265
00:12:49,365 --> 00:12:52,301
My fault. He wanted to
skip the usual protocols

266
00:12:52,302 --> 00:12:54,736
and advance the nanobot
to its next phase.

267
00:12:54,737 --> 00:12:56,505
Just wanted him
to go slowly.

268
00:12:56,506 --> 00:12:59,942
Unfortunately, Edwin and I
don't communicate very well.

269
00:12:59,943 --> 00:13:01,910
Hey, Mom, what's
this Jensen Project

270
00:13:01,911 --> 00:13:03,378
you guys
keep talking about?

271
00:13:03,379 --> 00:13:05,347
It's a group of
really smart people

272
00:13:05,348 --> 00:13:08,083
who work together to make
the world a better place.

273
00:13:08,084 --> 00:13:09,818
How come I've never
heard of it?

274
00:13:09,819 --> 00:13:12,621
Let's just say that anonymity
is important to us.

275
00:13:12,622 --> 00:13:14,623
- So how do you join?
- You don't.

276
00:13:14,624 --> 00:13:15,924
You have to be invited.

277
00:13:15,925 --> 00:13:17,893
Are you guys,
like, members?

278
00:13:17,894 --> 00:13:19,328
We were...

279
00:13:19,329 --> 00:13:20,696
once.

280
00:13:20,697 --> 00:13:22,764
Ms. Jensen, we have
security clearance

281
00:13:22,765 --> 00:13:25,234
to land in the compound.

282
00:13:37,480 --> 00:13:41,283
Your onco-gene research,
the glucose-monitoring device

283
00:13:41,284 --> 00:13:44,052
and your servomechanisms
for robotics...

284
00:13:44,053 --> 00:13:46,255
Truly transformative
work, Edwin.

285
00:13:46,256 --> 00:13:47,623
Thank you.

286
00:13:47,624 --> 00:13:50,459
But as we discussed,
it's your nanobot technology

287
00:13:50,460 --> 00:13:52,961
that most interests
my associates and me.

288
00:13:52,962 --> 00:13:54,463
Well, I can see why.

289
00:13:54,464 --> 00:13:56,765
We're this close
to a breakthrough

290
00:13:56,766 --> 00:13:59,201
that could change
medicine forever.

291
00:13:59,202 --> 00:14:00,602
Could?

292
00:14:01,905 --> 00:14:02,905
Will.

293
00:14:04,073 --> 00:14:05,407
Will change.

294
00:14:06,776 --> 00:14:08,744
What about
proprietary rights?

295
00:14:08,745 --> 00:14:10,445
Ours and ours alone.

296
00:14:10,446 --> 00:14:12,080
We fund it.
We own it.

297
00:14:12,081 --> 00:14:13,782
We do with it
as we please.

298
00:14:13,783 --> 00:14:15,617
The credit, however...

299
00:14:15,618 --> 00:14:17,619
it's all yours,

300
00:14:17,620 --> 00:14:19,388
along with a great
deal of money.

301
00:14:21,424 --> 00:14:22,991
I'll need full autonomy,

302
00:14:22,992 --> 00:14:24,993
over my staff, the lab,

303
00:14:24,994 --> 00:14:25,994
our process...

304
00:14:25,995 --> 00:14:27,229
Not a problem.

305
00:14:27,230 --> 00:14:29,565
You're the horse
we're backing, Edwin.

306
00:14:29,566 --> 00:14:31,466
And we're willing
to bet big.

307
00:14:34,537 --> 00:14:37,673
As soon as we process
you through security,

308
00:14:37,674 --> 00:14:39,541
we'll meet with Dr. James,

309
00:14:39,542 --> 00:14:42,778
get a progress report
on the search for Edwin.

310
00:14:43,913 --> 00:14:45,480
How are you feeling?

311
00:14:45,481 --> 00:14:49,151
Afraid. Afraid that coming
back here was a bad idea.

312
00:14:54,757 --> 00:14:55,958
Don't take that off.

313
00:14:55,959 --> 00:14:58,594
That'll give you access
to most of the compound.

314
00:14:58,595 --> 00:15:00,963
Things have definitely
changed around here.

315
00:15:00,964 --> 00:15:03,932
I remember when security used
to be your dad's hunting dogs.

316
00:15:03,933 --> 00:15:06,835
Unfortunately, we're
learning the hard way

317
00:15:06,836 --> 00:15:08,904
that even all this
isn't enough.

318
00:15:10,073 --> 00:15:11,840
So, Brody...

319
00:15:11,841 --> 00:15:13,642
since your folks
haven't told you

320
00:15:13,643 --> 00:15:15,043
about the Jensen Project,

321
00:15:15,044 --> 00:15:16,278
I'll bring you
up to speed

322
00:15:16,279 --> 00:15:17,713
on our way to
meet Dr. James.

323
00:15:17,714 --> 00:15:20,182
OK. Cool.

324
00:15:20,183 --> 00:15:21,650
The Jensen Project

325
00:15:21,651 --> 00:15:24,119
is one of the premier research
facilities in the world.

326
00:15:24,120 --> 00:15:26,655
It was founded by my father,
the late William Jensen.

327
00:15:26,656 --> 00:15:29,024
The Project is
a collective of great minds

328
00:15:29,025 --> 00:15:32,494
who not only theorize about
ways to improve the world

329
00:15:32,495 --> 00:15:34,262
but actually do it.

330
00:15:34,263 --> 00:15:37,132
These are just a few of our
more successful projects.

331
00:15:37,133 --> 00:15:39,001
Yeah, but you
didn't get credit.

332
00:15:39,002 --> 00:15:40,168
Other people did.

333
00:15:40,169 --> 00:15:42,571
If the group develops,
say, a new vaccine,

334
00:15:42,572 --> 00:15:44,940
it's given to
an organization like the CDC

335
00:15:44,941 --> 00:15:46,775
or the World
Health Organization.

336
00:15:46,776 --> 00:15:48,744
They get
the magazine covers.

337
00:15:48,745 --> 00:15:51,179
At Jensen,
the work is the reward.

338
00:15:51,180 --> 00:15:52,848
Ingrid, status report.

339
00:15:52,849 --> 00:15:54,282
Kendrick James.

340
00:15:54,283 --> 00:15:56,952
This is Brody,
Matt and Claire Thompson.

341
00:15:56,953 --> 00:15:58,120
He's the head of

342
00:15:58,121 --> 00:16:00,389
the Photonic and Acoustical
Engineering Department

343
00:16:00,390 --> 00:16:01,757
and our security chief.

344
00:16:01,758 --> 00:16:03,125
Glad you're here.

345
00:16:03,126 --> 00:16:05,527
So far we've got
27 pieces of missing tech.

346
00:16:05,528 --> 00:16:08,263
And counting!
It is worse than we thought.

347
00:16:08,264 --> 00:16:11,633
Biomedical Neuro-cog
and Robotics were tapped.

348
00:16:11,634 --> 00:16:14,636
Ginny, these are
the Thompsons.

349
00:16:14,637 --> 00:16:15,937
Hi. And bye.

350
00:16:15,938 --> 00:16:17,739
I gotta go see
if they also hit AI.

351
00:16:19,809 --> 00:16:21,576
Welcome back to Jensen.

352
00:16:23,146 --> 00:16:26,081
Ginny heads up our
Computer Sciences division.

353
00:16:26,082 --> 00:16:28,817
Let's get to it before
things get worse than they are.

354
00:16:28,818 --> 00:16:30,919
There's no telling
how far Edwin's gone.

355
00:16:30,920 --> 00:16:34,089
- Oh, what about me?
- Free to roam the premises.

356
00:16:34,090 --> 00:16:36,058
Stay out of trouble.

357
00:16:38,528 --> 00:16:39,861
No worries.

358
00:16:44,667 --> 00:16:46,468
<i>♪ Hurry up ♪</i>

359
00:16:46,469 --> 00:16:49,137
<i>♪ And wait ♪</i>

360
00:16:49,138 --> 00:16:51,139
<i>♪ So close ♪</i>

361
00:16:51,140 --> 00:16:54,176
<i>♪ But so far away ♪</i>

362
00:16:54,177 --> 00:16:58,480
<i>♪ Everything that</i>
<i>you always dreamed of ♪</i>

363
00:16:58,481 --> 00:17:00,949
<i>♪ Close enough</i>
<i>for you to taste ♪</i>

364
00:17:00,950 --> 00:17:03,118
♪ But you just can't touch ♪

365
00:17:03,119 --> 00:17:06,088
♪ You wanna show the world
but no one knows your name ♪

366
00:17:06,089 --> 00:17:08,824
♪ Wonder when and where
and how you're gonna make it ♪

367
00:17:08,825 --> 00:17:11,693
<i>♪ You know you can</i>
<i>if you get the chance... ♪</i>

368
00:17:11,694 --> 00:17:14,863
We know that more than
a billion people worldwide

369
00:17:14,864 --> 00:17:16,565
are without access
to clean water.

370
00:17:16,566 --> 00:17:17,899
And as a result,

371
00:17:17,900 --> 00:17:20,102
more than 4,000 children
in developing countries

372
00:17:20,103 --> 00:17:21,503
die every single day.

373
00:17:21,504 --> 00:17:23,939
So we created this
helpful little invention

374
00:17:23,940 --> 00:17:26,174
and gave it to
the good people at Pur.

375
00:17:27,376 --> 00:17:29,711
It usually takes
half an hour in a strainer,

376
00:17:29,712 --> 00:17:31,313
but we'll speed
things up here.

377
00:17:35,017 --> 00:17:36,318
And there you have it!

378
00:17:36,319 --> 00:17:38,653
Potentially deadly water
is now clean

379
00:17:38,654 --> 00:17:40,322
and ready to drink.

380
00:17:41,891 --> 00:17:45,460
The uses are infinite.
Non-toxic, water soluble.

381
00:17:46,796 --> 00:17:50,165
It can be used to heal
a bloody wound during battle

382
00:17:50,166 --> 00:17:52,801
or seal a leak
on the space shuttle.

383
00:17:52,802 --> 00:17:55,103
<i>♪ You believe</i>
<i>and you doubt ♪</i>

384
00:17:55,104 --> 00:17:57,773
<i>♪ You're confused</i>
<i>and got it all figured out ♪</i>

385
00:17:59,876 --> 00:18:04,246
<i>♪ Everything that you</i>
<i>always wished for ♪</i>

386
00:18:04,247 --> 00:18:07,182
♪ Could be yours, should be
<i>yours, would be yours ♪</i>

387
00:18:07,183 --> 00:18:08,884
<i>♪ If they only knew ♪</i>

388
00:18:08,885 --> 00:18:11,820
♪ You wanna show the world
but no one knows your name ♪

389
00:18:11,821 --> 00:18:14,556
♪ Wonder when and where
and how you're gonna make it ♪

390
00:18:14,557 --> 00:18:16,625
<i>♪ You know you can</i>
<i>if you get the chance ♪</i>

391
00:18:16,626 --> 00:18:18,860
<i>♪ In your face</i>
<i>as the door keeps slamming ♪</i>

392
00:18:18,861 --> 00:18:20,328
Whoa!

393
00:18:20,329 --> 00:18:22,264
<i>♪ You're feeling more</i>
<i>and more frustrated ♪</i>

394
00:18:22,265 --> 00:18:25,433
<i>♪ And you're getting</i>
<i>all kind of impatient waiting ♪</i>

395
00:18:25,434 --> 00:18:27,402
♪ We live and we learn ♪

396
00:18:27,403 --> 00:18:29,604
<i>♪ To take</i>
<i>one step at a time ♪</i>

397
00:18:29,605 --> 00:18:32,340
♪ There's no need to rush ♪

398
00:18:32,341 --> 00:18:34,476
♪ It's like learning to fly ♪

399
00:18:34,477 --> 00:18:37,612
<i>♪ Or falling in love ♪</i>

400
00:18:37,613 --> 00:18:39,080
<i>♪ It's gonna happen ♪</i>

401
00:18:39,081 --> 00:18:41,750
♪ When it's supposed to happen
<i>♪</i>

402
00:18:41,751 --> 00:18:43,418
<i>♪ And we find</i>
<i>a reason why ♪</i>

403
00:18:43,419 --> 00:18:44,820
<i></i> Sweet.

404
00:18:44,821 --> 00:18:48,223
<i>♪ One step at a time ♪</i>

405
00:18:49,559 --> 00:18:51,827
<i>Brody Thompson...</i>

406
00:18:51,828 --> 00:18:56,198
<i>you are not authorized</i>
<i>to be in this security zone.</i>

407
00:18:59,135 --> 00:19:00,769
Uh, sorry! Sorry!

408
00:19:00,770 --> 00:19:02,137
My bad!

409
00:19:05,074 --> 00:19:08,410
<i>♪ And we find</i>
<i>the reasons why ♪</i>

410
00:19:08,411 --> 00:19:11,446
<i>♪ One step at a time ♪</i>

411
00:19:11,447 --> 00:19:13,548
Whoa!

412
00:19:13,549 --> 00:19:15,650
Has anyone gone through
Edwin's stuff?

413
00:19:15,651 --> 00:19:17,018
What little
he left behind

414
00:19:17,019 --> 00:19:18,920
was in his
incomprehensible shorthand.

415
00:19:18,921 --> 00:19:21,723
It's based on an algorithm.
I helped him create it.

416
00:19:21,724 --> 00:19:23,358
I was so hoping
you'd say that!

417
00:19:23,359 --> 00:19:25,126
Sounds like he took
a lot of tech.

418
00:19:25,127 --> 00:19:27,162
Are you sure he's
focusing on nanobots?

419
00:19:27,163 --> 00:19:29,931
No, but based on our last
conversation, I'm guessing.

420
00:19:29,932 --> 00:19:32,434
Certainly the most
high-profile.

421
00:19:32,435 --> 00:19:34,502
And unfortunately,
the most dangerous.

422
00:19:34,503 --> 00:19:37,239
But he wasn't able to take
our molecular assembler.

423
00:19:37,240 --> 00:19:38,406
Your what?

424
00:19:38,407 --> 00:19:40,375
He can't produce
nanobots without it.

425
00:19:40,376 --> 00:19:41,776
And besides ours,

426
00:19:41,777 --> 00:19:44,079
there's only a few others
in the entire world.

427
00:19:44,080 --> 00:19:46,615
Well, I guess we should
roll up our sleeves.

428
00:19:46,616 --> 00:19:48,984
I'm going to need
all of Edwin's old files.

429
00:19:48,985 --> 00:19:50,452
I'll send them right away.

430
00:19:50,453 --> 00:19:52,120
You can work over here
at his desk.

431
00:19:52,121 --> 00:19:54,155
Who's running
Immunology these days?

432
00:19:54,156 --> 00:19:56,258
You are.
At least for now.

433
00:19:56,259 --> 00:19:58,860
Our department head
took off with Edwin.

434
00:19:58,861 --> 00:20:00,128
Can I access
lab records?

435
00:20:00,129 --> 00:20:02,764
Absolutely. Come on.
I'll walk with you.

436
00:20:09,739 --> 00:20:11,172
Monitor.

437
00:20:11,173 --> 00:20:12,841
Open files.

438
00:20:19,882 --> 00:20:21,449
Next file.

439
00:20:21,450 --> 00:20:24,152
I can't tell you
how much it means to me

440
00:20:24,153 --> 00:20:26,388
to have both of you
back here again.

441
00:20:26,389 --> 00:20:28,256
This wasn't easy,
you know,

442
00:20:28,257 --> 00:20:30,992
for Claire, I mean, not after
Edwin forced her to leave.

443
00:20:30,993 --> 00:20:32,127
I can imagine.

444
00:20:32,128 --> 00:20:34,396
You two ever talk about
the time you spent here?

445
00:20:34,397 --> 00:20:37,232
That's a subject that's been
pretty much off limits

446
00:20:37,233 --> 00:20:38,433
for a long time.

447
00:20:38,434 --> 00:20:41,536
Matt, I tried, actually,
to stand up to Edwin

448
00:20:41,537 --> 00:20:42,804
on Claire's behalf,

449
00:20:42,805 --> 00:20:44,873
but he was
absolutely adamant.

450
00:20:44,874 --> 00:20:46,841
His behavior
that day was...

451
00:20:47,910 --> 00:20:49,811
In retrospect,
it marked a change in him

452
00:20:49,812 --> 00:20:51,513
that continued
until the day he left.

453
00:20:53,082 --> 00:20:56,484
This is something you should
talk to Claire about,

454
00:20:56,485 --> 00:20:57,485
not me.

455
00:21:02,224 --> 00:21:04,592
Based on the list
you gave me,

456
00:21:04,593 --> 00:21:07,529
we've provided all the lab
equipment and installs.

457
00:21:07,530 --> 00:21:09,331
There's just one
piece of equipment

458
00:21:09,332 --> 00:21:10,598
we weren't
able to find.

459
00:21:10,599 --> 00:21:11,967
The molecular assembler.

460
00:21:11,968 --> 00:21:13,802
But my people
are working on that.

461
00:21:13,803 --> 00:21:16,104
Well, the sooner we
get our hands on one,

462
00:21:16,105 --> 00:21:18,306
the sooner I can start
producing nanobots.

463
00:21:31,954 --> 00:21:33,755
So what do you think?

464
00:21:36,926 --> 00:21:38,226
I think...

465
00:21:40,262 --> 00:21:41,596
...it's perfect!

466
00:21:41,597 --> 00:21:43,198
Excellent!

467
00:21:44,266 --> 00:21:47,235
Then I'll leave you
so you can get started.

468
00:22:04,820 --> 00:22:06,121
Hello?

469
00:23:18,494 --> 00:23:19,794
Hello?

470
00:23:28,270 --> 00:23:30,705
Oh, now,
this is beyond cool!

471
00:23:30,706 --> 00:23:32,207
Huh?

472
00:23:32,208 --> 00:23:33,842
Whoa!

473
00:23:38,768 --> 00:23:41,003
<i>You are in violation</i>
<i>of statute 387564,</i>

474
00:23:41,004 --> 00:23:42,371
<i>breaking and entering!</i>

475
00:23:42,372 --> 00:23:44,273
No, no, I was just
looking around!

476
00:23:44,274 --> 00:23:46,742
- <i>You hacked my security!</i>
<i>- You call that security?</i>

477
00:23:46,743 --> 00:23:48,577
<i>Uh, yeah!</i>
<i>I built it myself!</i>

478
00:23:48,578 --> 00:23:51,879
And I cracked it myself,
like, in 2 seconds!

479
00:23:51,982 --> 00:23:54,517
<i>Well, you're the one</i>
<i>hanging upside down!</i>

480
00:23:54,518 --> 00:23:56,186
- You ambushed me!
- <i>Who are you?</i>

481
00:23:56,187 --> 00:23:57,954
- Who are you?
- <i>I asked you first!</i>

482
00:23:57,955 --> 00:24:00,023
Look, just let me down,
and I promise--

483
00:24:00,024 --> 00:24:01,624
<i>Save it for the authorities!</i>

484
00:24:01,625 --> 00:24:04,360
No! No! Please! Come on!
Just don't call the cops!

485
00:24:04,361 --> 00:24:05,562
No! My mom would freak!

486
00:24:05,563 --> 00:24:07,630
- <i>Your parents know you're here?</i>
<i>- Yeah.</i>

487
00:24:07,631 --> 00:24:09,232
They're here, too.

488
00:24:09,233 --> 00:24:12,001
My mom used to work here
and so did my dad.

489
00:24:12,002 --> 00:24:13,837
- <i>No way!</i>
<i>- Oh yeah, for real!</i>

490
00:24:13,838 --> 00:24:15,271
Matthew and Claire Thompson.

491
00:24:15,272 --> 00:24:18,975
<i>You're Matt and</i>
<i>Claire Thompson's kid?</i>

492
00:24:18,976 --> 00:24:20,310
Well, then...

493
00:24:20,311 --> 00:24:22,645
you must be smarter
than you look!

494
00:24:24,982 --> 00:24:26,449
Next file.

495
00:24:26,450 --> 00:24:27,751
Next.

496
00:24:28,986 --> 00:24:30,787
Stop.

497
00:24:33,324 --> 00:24:34,524
Notes.

498
00:24:40,164 --> 00:24:41,998
Transfer file to tablet.

499
00:24:45,402 --> 00:24:46,770
Com.

500
00:24:46,771 --> 00:24:48,037
Kendrick.

501
00:24:48,038 --> 00:24:49,272
<i>Yes, Claire?</i>

502
00:24:50,574 --> 00:24:53,610
I found a notation
in one of Edwin's files.

503
00:24:53,611 --> 00:24:54,778
It's signed "NP."

504
00:24:54,779 --> 00:24:56,746
Any idea who that might be?

505
00:24:56,747 --> 00:24:59,549
The most obnoxious,
egocentric individual

506
00:24:59,550 --> 00:25:01,851
I've ever encountered.

507
00:25:01,852 --> 00:25:04,854
I'm not at all surprised
that Edwin's up and left.

508
00:25:04,855 --> 00:25:05,955
Good riddance!

509
00:25:05,956 --> 00:25:07,657
I take it you two
butted heads.

510
00:25:07,658 --> 00:25:08,892
Ah! Endlessly!

511
00:25:08,893 --> 00:25:10,727
Edwin made it
his personal goal

512
00:25:10,728 --> 00:25:13,263
